g an analysis of the struggles over 'proper burials'; the repatriation of dead migrants; abandoned cemeteries; exhumations; 'feminicide'; the protection of dead drug-lords; and the disappeared dead. Mapping theoretical and empirical terrains, this volume suggests that the management of dead bodies is related to the constitution and membership of states and non-state entities that claim autonomy and impunity.This volume is a significant contribution to studies of death, power and politics. It will be useful at both undergraduate and postgraduate levels in anthropology, sociology, law, criminology, political science, international relations, genocide studies, history, cultural studies and philosophy.The research program leading to publication has received funding from the European Research Council under the European Union's Seventh Framework Programme (FP/2007-2013) / ERC Grant Agreement n° 283-617.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSocial sciences. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aburial rituals.  acritical theory.  adead bodies.  amateriality.  apolitics.  apower.  apsychoanalysis.  asovereignty.  astructuralist-functionalist anthropology.  atransgression.  aviolence.1 aBorneman, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFontein, Joost, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKernaghan, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKristensen, Benedikte Møller, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKristensen, Regnar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMyrttinen, Henri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo